{"title_page": "Khiren Roy", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Dr. Khiren Roy\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = 21 June 1941\n| birth_place = Matia ([[Goalpara]]), [[Assam]]\n| death_date  = 11 March 2009\n| death_place = [[Guwahati]], [[Assam]]\n| education   = MA in English literature<br> PhD in Mass Communication\n| occupation  = Journalist<br> Newspaper Editor<br> Writer\n| alias       = \n| title       = Dr\n| family      = \n| spouse      = Gayatri Roy\n| domestic_partner =\n| children    = Arupa Roy Pathare<br> Antara Roy Oruganti\n| relatives   = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = \n| agent       = \n| URL         = http://www.khirenroy.com/\n}}\n\n'''Khiren Roy''' was a veteran journalist and editor to some English and Assamese Dailies published from [[Assam]].<ref name=\"ab\">{{cite web|url=http://news.gaeatimes.com/assamese-editor-khiren-roy-passes-away-17270/|title=Assamese editor Khiren Roy passes away|date=14 March 2009|publisher=Breaking News 24/7|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"cd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/03/12/stories/2009031255680700.htm|title=Veteran journalist Khiren Roy passes away |last=Talukdar|first=Sushanta|date=12 Mar 2009|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref> He was born at Matia, a hamlet in [[Goalpara]] district of  [[Assam]].<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Education==\nRoy completed his [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[English literature]] and [[PhD]] in [[Mass Communication]] from [[Gauhati University]]. He also participated in a higher course of journalism jointly organized by the Press Institute of India and the [[Thomson Foundation]], U.K.<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Career==\nRoy started his career as a staff reporter to ''[[The Assam Tribune]]'' and later became the Deputy Editor of it. He was also the editor of ''[[The North East Times]]'' and ''Meghalaya Guardian''. Then he established a publishing house named The Frontier Publication Pvt Ltd, launched the Assamese daily ''[[Asomiya Khobor]]'' and worked as the Chief editor of it.<ref name=\"ab\" /><ref name=\"cd\" /> He was also involved in teaching Journalism and Creative Writing at the [[Gauhati University]], [[Indira Gandhi National Open University]] at [[Guwahati]] and [[Shillong]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Works==\nRoy authored a number of novels and storybooks. [http://www.khirenroy.com/novels.php Here is a list of them].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Gayatri on 14 May 1975 and fathered two daughters \u2013 Arupa and Antara.<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn 11 March 2009, at the age of 68, Roy died following a [[cardiac failure]].<ref name=\"ab\" /><ref name=\"cd\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.khirenroy.com/ Khiren Roy\u2019s website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Khiren}}\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Goalpara district]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Gauhati University alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Assam]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n\n\n{{India-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Dr. Khiren Roy\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = 21 June 1941\n| birth_place = Matia ([[Goalpara]]), [[Assam]]\n| death_date  = 11 March 2009\n| death_place = [[Guwahati]], [[Assam]]\n| education   = MA in English literature<br> PhD in Mass Communication\n| occupation  = Journalist<br> Newspaper Editor<br> Writer\n| alias       = \n| title       = Dr\n| family      = \n| spouse      = Gayatri Roy\n| domestic_partner =\n| children    = Arupa Roy Pathare<br> Antara Roy Oruganti\n| relatives   = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = \n| agent       = \n| URL         = http://www.khirenroy.com/\n}}\n\n'''Khiren Roy''' was a veteran journalist and editor to some English and Assamese Dailies published from [[Assam]].<ref name=\"ab\">{{cite web|url=http://news.gaeatimes.com/assamese-editor-khiren-roy-passes-away-17270/|title=Assamese editor Khiren Roy passes away|date=14 March 2009|publisher=Breaking News 24/7|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"cd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/03/12/stories/2009031255680700.htm|title=Veteran journalist Khiren Roy passes away |last=Talukdar|first=Sushanta|date=12 Mar 2009|publisher=The Hindu|accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref> He was born at Matia, a hamlet in [[Goalpara]] district of  [[Assam]].<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Education==\nRoy completed his [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[English literature]] and [[PhD]] in [[Mass Communication]] from [[Gauhati University]]. He also participated in a higher course of journalism jointly organized by the Press Institute of India and the [[Thomson Foundation]], U.K.<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Career==\nRoy started his career as a staff reporter to ''[[The Assam Tribune]]'' and later became the Deputy Editor of it. He was also the editor of ''[[The North East Times]]'' and ''Meghalaya Guardian''. Then he established a publishing house named The Frontier Publication Pvt Ltd, launched the Assamese daily ''[[Asomiya Khobor]]'' and worked as the Chief editor of it.<ref name=\"ab\" /><ref name=\"cd\" /> He was also involved in teaching Journalism and Creative Writing at the [[Gauhati University]], [[Indira Gandhi National Open University]] at [[Guwahati]] and [[Shillong]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Works==\nRoy authored a number of novels and storybooks. [http://www.khirenroy.com/novels.php Here is a list of them].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married Gayatri on 14 May 1975 and fathered two daughters \u2013 Arupa and Antara.<ref name=\"ab\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn 11 March 2009, at the age of 68, Roy died following a [[cardiac failure]].<ref name=\"ab\" /><ref name=\"cd\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.khirenroy.com/ Khiren Roy\u2019s website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roy, Khiren}}\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Goalpara district]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Gauhati University alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Assam]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n\n\n{{India-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khiren_Roy"}
{"title_page": "Khatchig Mouradian", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{BLP self-published|date=November 2019}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{external links|date=November 2019}}\n{{Notability|date=March 2018}}\n}}\n\n'''Khatchig Mouradian''' is the Program Coordinator of the Armenian Genocide Program at the Center for the Study of Genocide, Conflict Resolution, and Human Rights [https://web.archive.org/web/20140502082109/http://www.ncas.rutgers.edu/khatchig-mouradian] at Rutgers University, where he also teaches in the History and Sociology departments. [http://armenianweekly.com/2014/10/29/rutgers-offers-two-new-courses-genocide/] He has also taught at [[Clark University]], [[Columbia University]]{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} and Worcester State University.\n\nMouradian was the editor of the Armenian Weekly from 2007-2014.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} He is the recipient the Gulbenkian Armenian Studies research fellowship to study the Armenian community in China in the 20th century (2014).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2014/09/29/research-project-explore-armenian-presence-china/|title=Research Project to Explore Armenian Presence in China|last=Staff|first=Weekly|date=2014-09-29|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Mouradian is also the recipient of the first Hrant Dink Freedom and Justice Medal (2014) of the Organization of Istanbul Armenians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222055410/http://oia.net/2014/01/23/los-angeles-community-honors-dink-legacy-asbarez/|title=Los Angeles Community Honors Dink Legacy (Asbarez) - Organization of Istanbul Armenians|date=2014-12-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Mouradian is a PhD Candidate at the Strassler Center for Holocaust and Genocide Studies at Clark University, currently completing his dissertation, titled \u201cGenocide and Humanitarian Resistance in Ottoman Syria, 1915-1917.\u201d[http://www.clarku.edu/departments/holocaust/phd/research.cfm].{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}}\n\nMouradian has lectured and participated in conferences in Armenia, Turkey, Cyprus, Lebanon, Syria, Austria, Switzerland, Norway, China, the United Arab Emirates and the United States.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} He has presented papers on [[genocide]] and the media at several academic conferences including the 5th and 6th [https://web.archive.org/web/20080724170146/http://www.armturkwokshop.org/workshop.html Workshops on Armenian-Turkish Scholarship],{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}} held at [[NYU]] in 2006 and at the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]] in 2008, an international conference titled \"The Armenian Genocide and International Law\" at [[Haigazian University]] in Beirut in September 2009, [http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/2009/09/09/international-conference-on-genocide-international-law-concludes-in-beirut/]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}} the 2010 \"The State of the Art of Armenian Genocide Research\" conference at Clark University [http://www.armenianweekly.com/2010/05/18/clark-conference/]\n\n, the 2010 Armenian Genocide conference in Ankara, Turkey [http://www.armenianweekly.com/2010/04/28/ankara-conference/], and the 2014 conference in Washington of the Society for Armenian Studies [http://armenianweekly.com/2014/12/17/sas-dc-conference/].\n\nIn 2009, Mouradian was the Seventh Arsham and Charlotte Ohanessian Lecturer at the University of Minnesota [https://web.archive.org/web/20090701042000/http://www.reporter.am/go/article/2009-06-26-armenians-started-using-the-word--genocide--in-1945-khatchig-mouradian-shows]. On April 24, 2010, Mouradian delivered a lecture on the Armenian Genocide in Istanbul, Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2010/04/24/genocide/|title=Mouradian: Despite Obstacles, Armenian Genocide Commemorations Held in Turkey|last=Mouradian|first=Khatchig|date=2010-04-25|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nMouradian was one of the junior editors of the Lebanese-Armenian daily newspaper Aztag from 2000 to 2007, when he moved to [[Boston]] and became the editor of the Armenian Weekly.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} Mouradian holds a B.S. in biology and has studied towards a graduate degree in [[clinical psychology]].<ref name=\"answer\" />{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2019}} He also holds a graduate certificate in Conflict Resolution and Management from the University of Massachusetts Boston [http://armenianweekly.com/2014/12/05/mouradian-in-motion/]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}}\n\nAs a journalist, Mouradian has interviewed leading scholars, authors and journalists like [[Noam Chomsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.chomsky.info/interviews/20060508.htm |title = Subordinate and Non-Subordinate States, Noam Chomsky interviewed by Khatchig Mouadian |accessdate = 2008-08-17 |author = Mouradian, Khatchig|date=2006-05-08}}</ref> [[Arundhati Roy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/16454 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211192530/http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/16454 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-11 |title=Interview with Arundhati Roy |work=ZNet |accessdate=2008-08-17 |date=2008-02-08 |author=Mouradian, Khatchig }}</ref> [[Paulo Coelho]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.jewcy.com/post/q_paulo_coelho# |title = Q &amp; A with Paulo Coelho |work=Jewcy|date=2008-03-25|accessdate = 2008-08-17}}</ref> [[Chris Bohjalian]]<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.hairenik.com/armenianweekly/NYS_122207_07.htm |title = An Interview with Chris Bohjalian|periodical=Armenian Weekly|accessdate = 2008-08-17|volume=73|issue=51\u201352|date=2007-12-22|postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> and [[Nicholas Kristof]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.hairenik.com/armenianweekly/fea04050802.htm |title = An interview with Nicholas D. Kristof|periodical=Armenian Weekly |accessdate = 2008-08-17|volume=74|issue=13|date=2008-04-05|postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents hail from [[Konya]], and [[Kilis]], while his maternal grandparents hail from [[Adana]], and [[Nur Mountains|Amanos]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}{{Relevance inline|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Writing==\nHis articles and poems<ref name=answer>{{cite web|url = http://groong.usc.edu/tlg/tlg-20030222.html |work= Literary Groong |publisher=Armenian News Network|title=Answer|author=Mouradian, Khatchig |accessdate = 2008-08-17|date=2003-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://groong.usc.edu/tlg/tlg-20021214.html|work= Literary Groong |publisher=Armenian News Network|title=Theft|author=Mouradian, Khatchig |accessdate = 2008-08-17|date=2002-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://armenian-poetry.blogspot.com/search/label/Khatchig%20Mouradian |work=Armenian Poetry Project|title =Khatchig Mouradian |accessdate = 2008-08-17}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} have appeared in publications worldwide. A few of his poems in languages other than English have been translated to English and are available online.[http://khatchigmouradian.blogspot.com/2006_12_01_archive.html]. Many of his writings have been translated into more than ten languages.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} He contributes to a number of U.S. and European publications, including [[ZNet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/zspace/khatchigmouradian |title=Khatchig Mouradian |work=Z Space }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} [[Jewcy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewcy.com/user/1836/khatchig_mouradian |title=Khatchig Mouradian |work=Jewcy |accessdate=2008-08-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513163414/http://www.jewcy.com/user/1836/khatchig_mouradian |archivedate=2008-05-13 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} [[The Jewish Advocate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=3731 |title=What would Lemkin do? |author=Mouradian, Khatchig |date=2008-08-17 |work=Jewish Advocate |accessdate=2008-08-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603142624/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=3731 |archivedate=2008-06-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=4201 |work=Jewish Advocate |title=An invitation to Musa Dagh |accessdate=2008-08-17 |author=Mouradian, Khatchig |date=2008-08-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312091339/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=4201 |archivedate=2008-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} and Radikal.[http://www.radikal.com.tr/Radikal.aspx?aType=RadikalHaberDetay&ArticleID=918637&Date=26.01.2009&CategoryID=99]\n\nThe special newspaper publications he has edited include \"[http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/download/3 Commemorating Genocide: Images, Perspectives, Research]\" and [http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/download/4 The Armenian Genocide].\n\nHe has one academic publication, \"From Yeghern To Genocide: Armenian Newspapers, Raphael Lemkin, And The Road To The UN Genocide Convention,\" (Haigazian Armenological Review, Vol.29, 2009).{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nHis translations (to Armenian) include [[Paulo Coelho]]'s \"[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]],\" published by [[Hamazkayin]] in 2004. The book was launched in Yerevan, Armenia in the presence of Coelho and Mouradian.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nHe judged the New England Poetry Club's 2007 Shelia Motton Book Award, the Jean Pedrick Chapbook Award [https://web.archive.org/web/20090213081015/http://www.nepoetryclub.org/contests2007.htm]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019|reason=The Sheila Motton award claim appears in the source. The Jean Pedrick Chapbook Award claim does not.}} and the 2008 Daniel Varoujan Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522112429/http://www.nepoetryclub.org/contests2008.htm|title=New England Poetry Club. Founded in 1915 by Amy Lowell, Robert Frost and Conrad Aiken.|date=2009-05-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.blogger.com/profile/06586890931026647735 Personal blog], [[Blogger.com]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mouradian, Khatchig}}\n[[Category:Armenian journalists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese Armenians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Clark University alumni]]\n[[Category:Armenian male writers]]\n[[Category:Clark University faculty]]\n[[Category:Worcester State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{self-published|date=November 2019}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{external links|date=November 2019}}}}{{Notability|date=March 2018}}\n\n'''Khatchig Mouradian''' is the Program Coordinator of the Armenian Genocide Program at the Center for the Study of Genocide, Conflict Resolution, and Human Rights [https://web.archive.org/web/20140502082109/http://www.ncas.rutgers.edu/khatchig-mouradian] at Rutgers University, where he also teaches in the History and Sociology departments. [http://armenianweekly.com/2014/10/29/rutgers-offers-two-new-courses-genocide/] He has also taught at [[Clark University]], [[Columbia University]]{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} and Worcester State University.\n\nMouradian was the editor of the Armenian Weekly from 2007-2014.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} He is the recipient the Gulbenkian Armenian Studies research fellowship to study the Armenian community in China in the 20th century (2014).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2014/09/29/research-project-explore-armenian-presence-china/|title=Research Project to Explore Armenian Presence in China|last=Staff|first=Weekly|date=2014-09-29|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Mouradian is also the recipient of the first Hrant Dink Freedom and Justice Medal (2014) of the Organization of Istanbul Armenians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222055410/http://oia.net/2014/01/23/los-angeles-community-honors-dink-legacy-asbarez/|title=Los Angeles Community Honors Dink Legacy (Asbarez) - Organization of Istanbul Armenians|date=2014-12-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Mouradian is a PhD Candidate at the Strassler Center for Holocaust and Genocide Studies at Clark University, currently completing his dissertation, titled \u201cGenocide and Humanitarian Resistance in Ottoman Syria, 1915-1917.\u201d[http://www.clarku.edu/departments/holocaust/phd/research.cfm].{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}}\n\nMouradian has lectured and participated in conferences in Armenia, Turkey, Cyprus, Lebanon, Syria, Austria, Switzerland, Norway, China, the United Arab Emirates and the United States.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} He has presented papers on [[genocide]] and the media at several academic conferences including the 5th and 6th [https://web.archive.org/web/20080724170146/http://www.armturkwokshop.org/workshop.html Workshops on Armenian-Turkish Scholarship],{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}} held at [[NYU]] in 2006 and at the [[Graduate Institute of International Studies]] in [[Geneva]] in 2008, an international conference titled \"The Armenian Genocide and International Law\" at [[Haigazian University]] in Beirut in September 2009, [http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/2009/09/09/international-conference-on-genocide-international-law-concludes-in-beirut/]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}} the 2010 \"The State of the Art of Armenian Genocide Research\" conference at Clark University [http://www.armenianweekly.com/2010/05/18/clark-conference/]\n\n, the 2010 Armenian Genocide conference in Ankara, Turkey[http://www.armenianweekly.com/2010/04/28/ankara-conference/], and the 2014 conference in Washington of the Society for Armenian Studies [http://armenianweekly.com/2014/12/17/sas-dc-conference/].\n\nIn 2009, Mouradian was the Seventh Arsham and Charlotte Ohanessian Lecturer at the University of Minnesota [https://web.archive.org/web/20090701042000/http://www.reporter.am/go/article/2009-06-26-armenians-started-using-the-word--genocide--in-1945-khatchig-mouradian-shows]. On April 24, 2010, Mouradian delivered a lecture on the Armenian Genocide in Istanbul, Turkey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2010/04/24/genocide/|title=Mouradian: Despite Obstacles, Armenian Genocide Commemorations Held in Turkey|last=Mouradian|first=Khatchig|date=2010-04-25|website=The Armenian Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nMouradian was one of the junior editors of the Lebanese-Armenian daily newspaper Aztag from 2000 to 2007, when he moved to [[Boston]] and became the editor of the Armenian Weekly.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} Mouradian holds a B.S. in biology and has studied towards a graduate degree in [[clinical psychology]].<ref name=\"answer\" />{{Unreliable source?|date=November 2019}} He also holds a graduate certificate in Conflict Resolution and Management from the University of Massachusetts Boston[http://armenianweekly.com/2014/12/05/mouradian-in-motion/]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019}}\n\nAs a journalist, Mouradian has interviewed leading scholars, authors and journalists like [[Noam Chomsky]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.chomsky.info/interviews/20060508.htm |title = Subordinate and Non-Subordinate States, Noam Chomsky interviewed by Khatchig Mouadian |accessdate = 2008-08-17 |author = Mouradian, Khatchig|date=2006-05-08}}</ref> [[Arundhati Roy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/16454 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211192530/http://www.zmag.org/znet/viewArticle/16454 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-11 |title=Interview with Arundhati Roy |work=ZNet |accessdate=2008-08-17 |date=2008-02-08 |author=Mouradian, Khatchig }}</ref> [[Paulo Coelho]],<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.jewcy.com/post/q_paulo_coelho# |title = Q &amp; A with Paulo Coelho |work=Jewcy|date=2008-03-25|accessdate = 2008-08-17}}</ref> [[Chris Bohjalian]]<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.hairenik.com/armenianweekly/NYS_122207_07.htm |title = An Interview with Chris Bohjalian|periodical=Armenian Weekly|accessdate = 2008-08-17|volume=73|issue=51\u201352|date=2007-12-22|postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> and [[Nicholas Kristof]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.hairenik.com/armenianweekly/fea04050802.htm |title = An interview with Nicholas D. Kristof|periodical=Armenian Weekly |accessdate = 2008-08-17|volume=74|issue=13|date=2008-04-05|postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nHis paternal grandparents hail from [[Konya]], and [[Kilis]], while his maternal grandparents hail from [[Adana]], and [[Nur Mountains|Amanos]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}{{Relevance inline|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Writing==\nHis articles and poems<ref name=answer>{{cite web|url = http://groong.usc.edu/tlg/tlg-20030222.html |work= Literary Groong |publisher=Armenian News Network|title=Answer|author=Mouradian, Khatchig |accessdate = 2008-08-17|date=2003-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://groong.usc.edu/tlg/tlg-20021214.html|work= Literary Groong |publisher=Armenian News Network|title=Theft|author=Mouradian, Khatchig |accessdate = 2008-08-17|date=2002-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://armenian-poetry.blogspot.com/search/label/Khatchig%20Mouradian |work=Armenian Poetry Project|title =Khatchig Mouradian |accessdate = 2008-08-17}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} have appeared in publications worldwide. A few of his poems in languages other than English have been translated to English and are available online.[http://khatchigmouradian.blogspot.com/2006_12_01_archive.html]. Many of his writings have been translated into more than ten languages.{{cn|date=February 2020}} He contributes to a number of U.S. and European publications, including [[ZNet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zmag.org/zspace/khatchigmouradian |title=Khatchig Mouradian |work=Z Space }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} [[Jewcy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewcy.com/user/1836/khatchig_mouradian |title=Khatchig Mouradian |work=Jewcy |accessdate=2008-08-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513163414/http://www.jewcy.com/user/1836/khatchig_mouradian |archivedate=2008-05-13 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} [[The Jewish Advocate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=3731 |title=What would Lemkin do? |author=Mouradian, Khatchig |date=2008-08-17 |work=Jewish Advocate |accessdate=2008-08-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080603142624/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=3731 |archivedate=2008-06-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=4201 |work=Jewish Advocate |title=An invitation to Musa Dagh |accessdate=2008-08-17 |author=Mouradian, Khatchig |date=2008-08-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312091339/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/opinions/?content_id=4201 |archivedate=2008-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2019}} and Radikal.[http://www.radikal.com.tr/Radikal.aspx?aType=RadikalHaberDetay&ArticleID=918637&Date=26.01.2009&CategoryID=99]\n\nThe special newspaper publications he has edited include \"[http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/download/3 Commemorating Genocide: Images, Perspectives, Research]\" and [http://www.hairenik.com/weekly/download/4 The Armenian Genocide].\n\nHe has one academic publication, \"From Yeghern To Genocide: Armenian Newspapers, Raphael Lemkin, And The Road To The UN Genocide Convention,\" (Haigazian Armenological Review, Vol.29, 2009).{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nHis translations (to Armenian) include [[Paulo Coelho]]'s \"[[The Alchemist (novel)|The Alchemist]],\" published by [[Hamazkayin]] in 2004. The book was launched in Yerevan, Armenia in the presence of Coelho and Mouradian.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nHe judged the New England Poetry Club's 2007 Shelia Motton Book Award, the Jean Pedrick Chapbook Award [https://web.archive.org/web/20090213081015/http://www.nepoetryclub.org/contests2007.htm]{{Failed verification|date=November 2019|reason=The Sheila Motton award claim appears in the source. The Jean Pedrick Chapbook Award claim does not.}} and the 2008 Daniel Varoujan Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522112429/http://www.nepoetryclub.org/contests2008.htm|title=New England Poetry Club. Founded in 1915 by Amy Lowell, Robert Frost and Conrad Aiken.|date=2009-05-22|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.blogger.com/profile/06586890931026647735 Personal blog], [[Blogger.com]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mouradian, Khatchig}}\n[[Category:Armenian journalists]]\n[[Category:Lebanese Armenians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Clark University alumni]]\n[[Category:Armenian male writers]]\n[[Category:Clark University faculty]]\n[[Category:Worcester State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khatchig_Mouradian"}
{"title_page": "Dexter Bean", "text_new": "{{short description|American racing driver}}\n{{Infobox NASCAR driver\n|name               = Dexter Bean\n|image              = Dexter Bean Road America 2017.jpg\n|caption            = Bean at [[Road America]] in 2017\n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|1|5}}\n|birth_place        = [[Westby, Wisconsin]]\n|achievements       = \n|awards             = \n|Total_Cup_Races    = 1\n|Years_In_Cup       = 1\n|Cup_Car_Team       = \n|Prev_Cup_Pos       = 63rd\n|Previous_Year      = 2009\n|Best_Cup_Pos       = 63rd ([[2009 NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|2009]])\n|First_Cup_Race     = [[2009 NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|2009]] [[Pocono 500]] ([[Pocono Raceway|Pocono]])\n|Last_Cup_Race      = \n|First_Cup_Win      =\n|Last_Cup_Win       =\n|Cup_Wins           = 0\n|Cup_Top_Tens       = 0\n|Cup_Poles          = 0\n|Total_Busch_Races  = 16\n|Years_In_Busch     = 5\n|Busch_Car_Team     = No. 90 ([[DGM Racing]])\n|Prev_Busch_Pos     = 78th\n|Prev_Busch_Year    = 2019\n|Best_Busch_Pos     = 54th ([[2016 NASCAR Xfinity Series|2016]])\n|First_Busch_Race   = [[2006 NASCAR Busch Series|2006]] [[Sam's Town 250]] ([[Memphis Motorsports Park|Memphis]])\n|Last_Busch_Race    = [[2\n|Truck_Car_Team     = \n|Prev_Truck_Pos     = 58th\n|Prev_Truck_Year    = 2009\n|Best_Truck_Pos     = 58th ([[2009 NASCAR Camping World Truck Series|2009]])\n|First_Truck_Race   = [[2009 NASCAR Camping World Truck Series|2009]] [[AAA Insurance 200 (Dover)|AAA Insurance 200]] ([[Dover International Speedway|Dover]])\n|Last_Truck_Race    = [[2009 NASCAR Camping World Truck Series|2009]] [[Copart 200 (Gateway)|Copart 200]] ([[Gateway International Raceway|Gateway]])\n|First_Truck_Win    = \n|Last_Truck_Win     = \n|Truck_Wins         = 0\n|Truck_Top_Tens     = 0\n|Truck_Poles        = 0\n|updated            = November 18, 2019\n}}\n'''Dexter Bean''' (born January 5, 1987) is an American professional [[stock car racing]] driver. A veteran of the [[ARCA Racing Series]], he has also competed in selected events in all three of [[NASCAR]]'s national touring series. He currently competes part-time in the [[NASCAR Xfinity Series]], driving the No. 90 [[Chevrolet Camaro (sixth generation)|Chevrolet Camaro SS]] for [[DGM Racing]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBean was born in [[Westby, Wisconsin]] on January 5, 1987.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dexterbean.net/pages/bio.html|title=Dexter Bean Bio|publisher=Dexter Bean official site|accessdate=2012-08-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308040532/http://www.dexterbean.net/pages/bio.html|archive-date=2012-03-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|type 1 diabetes]].<ref name=mullins>Mullins, Christy. \"[http://www.heraldonline.com/2007/06/15/52680/tega-cays-joseph-bass-is-dc-bound.html Tega Cay's Joseph Bass is D.C. bound] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129015655/http://www.heraldonline.com/2007/06/15/52680/tega-cays-joseph-bass-is-dc-bound.html |date=2012-01-29 }}\", The Herald (Rock Hill, South Carolina), June 15, 2007.</ref> Bean is married to former Ms. North Carolina, Misty McCrary. Together they have two daughters, Marley Mae, born in November 2013, and Moxley Drew, born in November 2015.\n\n==Racing career==\nBean began his racing career at age 10 in [[kart racing|go-karts]], and switched to stock cars at the age of 16, driving for family-owned [[BlackJack Racing]];<ref name=\"Bio\"/> the team was named after Bean's father, David, used his winnings from a gambling trip to [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] to start the team.<ref name=\"Pickett\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CXwlAAAAIBAJ&sjid=nvQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4145,3157819&dq=dexter-bean+third+arca&hl=en|title=For Midwest driver, a future in racing is all in the cards|last=Minter|first=Rick|date=August 30, 2007|work=[[Gettysburg Times]]|page=C4|accessdate=2012-08-28|location=Gettysburg, PA}}</ref> After competing in [[late model]] competition at [[LaCrosse Fairgrounds Speedway]],<ref name=\"MJS\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dXAeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=E0cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6581,2294243&dq=dexter-bean&hl=en|title=Young Wisconsin driver has it all, except a victory|last=Kallmann|first=Dave|date=August 25, 2007|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|page=8C|accessdate=2012-08-28|location=Milwaukee, WI}}</ref> Bean moved to regional touring competition in the [[Wisconsin Challenge Series]] and the [[ARTGO|NASCAR AutoZone Elite Series Midwest Division]] before moving to the [[ARCA Racing Series]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Competing with BlackJack Racing between 2005 and 2007 in all but his very first race in the series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/rquery?id=beande01&trk=t0&series=A|title=Dexter Bean - ARCA Racing Series Results|work=Racing-Reference|publisher=USA Today Sports Media Group|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> Bean posted a best points finish of third at the end of the 2007 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/2007/news/headlines/cup/12/13/drive.diversity.struggles.strides/1.html|title=Diversity still a struggle for NASCAR despite programs|last=Swan|first=Raygan|date=December 14, 2007|work=NASCAR.com|publisher=Turner Sports|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> Bean also tested a [[Craftsman Truck Series]] truck for [[Germain Racing]] during 2007.<ref name=\"MJS\"/>\n[[File:90 Dexter Bean 2017 Johnsonville 180.jpg|thumb|left|Bean in his home state Xfinity race at [[Road America]] in 2017]]\nHaving run a single [[Busch Series]] race for [[Spraker Racing Enterprises]] in 2006, Bean rejoined Spraker for the 2008 ARCA Racing Series season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carsandracingstuff.com/library/articles/1200.php|title=GLOCK, Inc. Announces Dexter Bean will drive No. 37 GLOCK Chevrolet and Contract Renewal with Spraker Racing Enterprises for 2008 ARCA RE/MAX Series Season|last=Knight|first=Chris|date=November 8, 2007|publisher=Spraker Racing Enterprises|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> finishing 11th in points. For the 2009 season, Bean moved to the [[Sprint Cup Series]] with his family-owned team, attempting to run for the series' [[NASCAR Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] award. After failing to qualify for races at [[Las Vegas Motor Speedway]] and [[Phoenix International Raceway]], Bean qualified the No. 51 Dodge for the [[Pocono 500]] at [[Pocono Raceway]], starting 41st and finishing 36th, four laps behind race winner [[Tony Stewart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/tom_bowles/06/09/power.rankings/|title=Tony Stewart stays on top with Pocono win|last=Bowles|first=Tom|date=June 9, 2009|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> Bean failed to qualify for races at [[New Hampshire Motor Speedway]] and [[Chicagoland Speedway]] later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/drivdet/beande01/2009/W|title=Dexter Bean -  2009 NASCAR Sprint Cup Results|work=Racing-Reference|publisher=USA Today Sports Media Group|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> Bean also ran three Craftsman Truck Series races in 2009, driving trucks for [[Mario Gosselin (racing driver)|Mario Gosselin]] in events at [[Dover International Speedway]] and [[The Milwaukee Mile]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catchfence.com/2009/truckseries/06/16/dexter-bean-to-make-second-nascar-camping-world-truck-series-start-at-the-milwaukee-mile/|title=Dexter Bean To Make Second NASCAR Camping World Truck Series Start At The Milwaukee Mile|date=June 16, 2009|publisher=Catchfence.com|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> and for [[Tagsby Racing]] at [[Gateway International Raceway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/252194-sms-camping-world-update-issue-no-52|title=S.M.'s Camping World Update, Issue No. 52|last=Fan|first=Horn|date=September 10, 2009|work=Bleacher Report|publisher=Turner Sports|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref> posting a best finish of 17th at Milwaukee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.racing-reference.info/rquery?id=beande01&trk=t0&series=C|title=Dexter Bean - NASCAR Camping World Truck Series Results|work=Racing-Reference|publisher=USA Today Sports Media Group|accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref>\n\nAfter a two-year hiatus from racing in NASCAR, Bean returned to the Nationwide, now [[Xfinity Series]], in the No. 92 [[King Autosport]] Chevy at [[Daytona International Speedway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nascar.com/content/nascar/en_us/news-media/articles/2015/2/16/king-autosport-two-xfinity-cars-at-daytona-alert-today-florida-300.html|title=KING AUTOSPORT FIELDING TWO XFINITY CARS AT DAYTONA|work=[[NASCAR]]|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2015}}</ref> After failing to qualify at [[Las Vegas Motor Speedway]], Bean replaced [[Joey Gase]] in the No. 52 [[Jimmy Means Racing]] Chevy after Gase suffered food poisoning prior to the race; Gase started the race, and Bean took over during the event.<ref>{{cite web|last=Knight|first=Chris|url=http://www.catchfence.com/2015/press/03/07/dexter-bean-standby-joey-gase-las-vegas|title=Dexter Bean On Standby For Joey Gase In Las Vegas|publisher=Catchfence|date=March 7, 2015|accessdate=March 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2019 NASCAR Xfinity Series|2019]], Bean announced his return to Xfinity competition at [[2019 CTECH Manufacturing 180|Road America]]. driving the [[DGM Racing]] No. 90 Chevrolet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tobychristie.com/2019/08/19/dexter-bean-returns-to-xfinity-series-competition-at-road-america/ |title=Dexter Bean Returns to Xfinity Series Competition at Road America |first=Toby |last=Christie |website=TobyChristie.com |date=August 19, 2019 |accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsports career results==\n\n===NASCAR===\n([[Template:NASCAR driver results legend|key]]) (<span style=\"font-size:85%\">'''Bold'''&nbsp;\u2013 Pole position awarded by qualifying time. ''Italics''&nbsp;\u2013 Pole position earned by points standings or practice time. *&nbsp;\u2013 Most laps led.</span>)\n\n====Sprint Cup S